  "stimulus": "Consider the function $f(x) = \\dfrac{1}{x^2 - kx}$, where $k$ is a nonzero constant. The derivative of $f$ is given by $f'(x) = \\dfrac{k - 2x}{\\left(x^2 - kx\\right)^2}$.",
  "stimulus_image": null,
  "documents": null,
  "parts": [
    {
      "letter": "a",
      "prompt": "Let $k = 3$, so that $f(x) = \\dfrac{1}{x^2 - 3x}$. Write an equation for the line tangent to the graph of $f$ at the point whose $x$-coordinate is $4$.",
      "point_value": 2,
      "scoring_notes": null,
      "requires_drawing": false,
      "reference_image": null,
      "scoring_points": [
        {
          "point_id": "a1",
          "point_value": 1,
          "description": "Correct slope using $f'(4)$ with $k = 3$: $f(4) = \\dfrac{1}{16 - 12} = \\dfrac{1}{4}$ and $f'(4) = \\dfrac{3 - 8}{(16 - 12)^2} = \\dfrac{-5}{16}$",
          "alternatives": [
            {
              "required_elements": [
                "$f'(4) = \\dfrac{3 - 8}{(4^2 - 12)^2} = -\\dfrac{5}{16}$"
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "point_id": "a2",
          "point_value": 1,
          "description": "Correct tangent line equation using point-slope form: $y - \\dfrac{1}{4} = -\\dfrac{5}{16}(x - 4)$",
          "alternatives": [
            {
              "required_elements": [
                "$y - \\dfrac{1}{4} = -\\dfrac{5}{16}(x - 4)$"
              ]
            },
            {
              "required_elements": [
                "$y = -\\dfrac{5}{16}x + \\dfrac{5}{4} + \\dfrac{1}{4} = -\\dfrac{5}{16}x + \\dfrac{6}{4}$"
              ]
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "letter": "b",
      "prompt": "Let $k = 4$, so that $f(x) = \\dfrac{1}{x^2 - 4x}$. Determine whether $f$ has a relative minimum, a relative maximum, or neither at $x = 2$. Justify your answer.",
      "point_value": 2,
      "scoring_notes": null,
      "requires_drawing": false,
      "reference_image": null,
      "scoring_points": [
        {
          "point_id": "b1",
          "point_value": 1,
          "description": "Evaluates $f'(2)$ with $k = 4$: $f'(2) = \\dfrac{4 - 4}{(4 - 8)^2} = \\dfrac{0}{16} = 0$, so $x = 2$ is a critical point",
          "alternatives": [
            {
              "required_elements": [
                "$f'(2) = 0$, confirming $x = 2$ is a critical point"
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "point_id": "b2",
          "point_value": 1,
          "description": "Correct sign analysis: $f'(x) = \\dfrac{4 - 2x}{(x^2 - 4x)^2}$. The denominator is always positive (where defined), so the sign of $f'$ depends on $4 - 2x$: positive for $x < 2$ and negative for $x > 2$. Therefore $f$ has a relative maximum at $x = 2$.",
          "alternatives": [
            {
              "required_elements": [
                "$f'$ changes from positive to negative at $x = 2$",
                "Relative maximum at $x = 2$"
              ]
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "letter": "c",
      "prompt": "Find the value of $k$ for which $f$ has a critical point at $x = -5$.",
      "point_value": 1,
      "scoring_notes": null,
      "requires_drawing": false,
      "reference_image": null,
      "scoring_points": [
        {
          "point_id": "c1",
          "point_value": 1,
          "description": "Sets $f'(-5) = 0$: the numerator $k - 2(-5) = k + 10 = 0$, so $k = -10$",
          "alternatives": [
            {
              "required_elements": [
                "$k - 2(-5) = 0 \\Rightarrow k + 10 = 0 \\Rightarrow k = -10$"
              ]
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "letter": "d",
      "prompt": "Let $k = 6$, so that $f(x) = \\dfrac{1}{x^2 - 6x}$. Find the partial fraction decomposition for $f(x)$. Use the partial fractions to find $\\int f(x)\\,dx$.",
      "point_value": 4,
      "scoring_notes": null,
      "requires_drawing": false,
      "reference_image": null,
      "scoring_points": [
        {
          "point_id": "d1",
          "point_value": 1,
          "description": "Correct factoring and partial fraction setup: $\\dfrac{1}{x(x-6)} = \\dfrac{A}{x} + \\dfrac{B}{x-6}$",
          "alternatives": [
            {
              "required_elements": [
                "$\\dfrac{1}{x(x-6)} = \\dfrac{A}{x} + \\dfrac{B}{x-6}$"
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "point_id": "d2",
          "point_value": 1,
          "description": "Correct coefficients: $1 = A(x-6) + Bx$. At $x = 0$: $A = -\\frac{1}{6}$. At $x = 6$: $B = \\frac{1}{6}$",
          "alternatives": [
            {
              "required_elements": [
                "$A = -\\dfrac{1}{6}$, $B = \\dfrac{1}{6}$"
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "point_id": "d3",
          "point_value": 1,
          "description": "Correct integral setup: $\\int f(x)\\,dx = \\int \\left(-\\dfrac{1}{6x} + \\dfrac{1}{6(x-6)}\\right)dx$",
          "alternatives": [
            {
              "required_elements": [
                "$\\int \\left(-\\dfrac{1}{6x} + \\dfrac{1}{6(x-6)}\\right)dx$"
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "point_id": "d4",
          "point_value": 1,
          "description": "Correct antiderivative: $-\\dfrac{1}{6}\\ln|x| + \\dfrac{1}{6}\\ln|x-6| + C = \\dfrac{1}{6}\\ln\\left|\\dfrac{x-6}{x}\\right| + C$",
          "alternatives": [
            {
              "required_elements": [
                "$\\dfrac{1}{6}\\ln\\left|\\dfrac{x-6}{x}\\right| + C$"
